title: Inelastic scattering of 100 MeV protons from 12C using a Ge(Li) total-absorption proton counter

x4freetext: Inelastic scattering of 100 MeV protons from 12C
using a Ge(Li) total-absorption proton counter

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Canadian Journal of Physics, Vol.48, Issue.2, p.201 (1970)

x4freetext: McGill synchrocyclotron.
The Ge(Li) detector had a total active volume
of 26.1 mm x 10 mm x 7 mm, the last dimension
corresponding to the drift depth. The detector is
sufficiently long (26 mm) to stop 100 MeV protons,
provided that they enter the detector in a direction
parallel to the junction surfaces.
The carbon target was natural carbon (1.1% 13C) in
graphite form, and was milled to 0.0134 in. thickness
with parallel surfaces. The thickness of the target
at its center was very uniform and was measured to be
A cooled Ge(Li) detector has been used as a total-
absorption proton counter for the energy analysis of
100 MeV protons scattered from a target of natural
carbon.
